# General Coding Standards

- Read nearby code before editing and follow existing module boundaries.
- Prefer clarity over cleverness and small functions over broad control flows.
- Add an abstraction only when it reduces real duplication or clarifies a
  repeated concept.
- Preserve public APIs and compatibility re-exports when reorganizing modules.
- Avoid unrelated refactors, formatting churn, or metadata changes.
- Do not add unnecessary dependencies.
- Use meaningful names. Short mathematical symbols are acceptable when they
  correspond to standard equations and are documented nearby.
- Add comments only for non-obvious reasoning, equations, or scientific
  assumptions.
- Never make destructive git changes or overwrite user data without explicit
  permission.
